Intro: Experiments and Causality

A Motivating Example

Research question: how does immigration shape natives’ political attitudes?

Hypothesis: according to conflict theory, exposure to immigration should generate feelings of group threat and lead to an increase in exclusionary attitudes amongst “natives”

“Typical” research design and results:

  • conduct a large-N survey measuring exclusionary attitudes
  • regress attitudes on (change in) percentage of immigrants in the local area


Class Questions:

  1. What conclusions would you draw from this study about the causal effect of immigration on exclusionary attitudes?
  2. Compare this observational study against an experimental design. What are the main differences between the two methodologies?
  3. Which study do you find more convincing?

Randomization and Causality

In experiments, the credibility of causal claims is not based on whether the model includes the “right” controls (or has the “right” functional form).

Rather, evidence of causality rests on the procedure by which individuals / units are sorted into treatment and control groups.

Random assignment implies that any (observed and unobserved) factors that affect outcomes are (on average) equally likely to be present in the treatment and control groups. Thus the treatment itself is the only systematic driver of differences in outcomes.

Example Balance Table


Class Question:

  1. Many programs strive to help students prepare for college entrance exams, such as the SAT. In an effort to study the effectiveness of these preparatory programs, a researcher draws a random sample of students attending public high school in the United States, and compares the SAT scores of those who took a preparatory class to those who did not. Is this an experiment or an observational study?

Field Experiments

Field experiments combine randomization with:

  • naturalist / authentic interventions
  • attention to realistic outcomes and consequential behaviors
  • (possibly) unobtrusive measurement
  • diverse “real-world” samples and settings

These features set field experiments apart from survey and lab experiments.

Additionally, these features may be consequetial for the inferences that researchers draw.

Discrimination Example


In the context of labor market discrimination, researchers are often interested in whether minority job applicants are less likely to be hired than (equally qualified) majority applicants.

To answer this question, imagine that some researchers create CVs for two fictitious job applicants. The CVs are identical, except that one applicant is named “Connor Williams” while the other is named “Deshaun Williams”.

Compare the following two experimental approaches:

A. Researchers recruit a sample of HR managers to participate in a survey experiment. Each HR manager is asked to evaluate one of the two CVs (randomly selected), and then indicate whether they would invite this person to interview for a job opening at their firm. Researchers compare the percentage of positive responses elicited by “Connor” vs “Deshaun.”

B. Researchers compile a list of job openings from jobs.com, and send one (randomly selected) CV to each job advertisement. Researchers then compare the number of callbacks elicited by “Connor” vs “Deshaun.”


Political Information Example


Recent increases in political polarization have been linked to the rise of (online) “echo chambers”, wherein individuals only seek out political information that confirms their pre-existing views.

Against this backdrop, some researchers want to find out whether exposing individuals to countervailing political information can reduce polarization.

Compare the following two experimental designs:

A. Researchers identify a sample of conservative voters from public records. These individuals are invited to take part in an online survey. Survey respondents are randomly divided into treatment and control groups. Respondents in the treatment group are asked to read a series of news articles from a liberal media outlet, before answering a series of questions about their political attitudes. Respondents in the control group are asked to simply answer the political attitude questions.

B. Researchers identify a sample of conservative voters from public records. This is sample is randomly divided into treatment and control groups. Households in the treatment group are sent a free subscription to a liberal newspaper for one month. At the end of the month, researchers conduct an online survey measuring political attitudes.


Class Questions:

  1. Which design would yield larger treatment effects? Why?
  2. Which design do you find more convincing?

Field experiments can also play diverse roles within the context of a larger line of research.

Field experiments often come in the form of randomized control trials (RCTs), which evaluate the effectiveness of a particular policy. Such studies are common in development economics, but also consider A/B testing:

RCTs are often criticized for being atheoretical. That is, we know that intervention X has Y effect in context Z, but we don’t know why, and we don’t know whether the result generalizes to other people and places.

At the other end of the spectrum, some field experiments have been designed as behavioral tests of basic theory. See this study.

Here’s a good example of a (short) study that uses social norms theory to inform the design of policies to reduce household energy consumption. The resulting field experiment constitutes both an evaluation of programme effectiveness as well as a “test” of the underlying theory.

Potential Outcomes

Going back to our SAT example, what does it mean to say that college prep courses have a causal effect on SAT scores?

Illustration of potential outcomes, depending on whether an individual takes a prep course
SAT if no prep SAT if prep Difference
Alex 650 670 20
Bonnie 500 580 80
Colin 550 550 0
Danielle 700 690 -10
Earl 600 660 60
Fiona 650 720 70
Gaston 400 580 180
Hermine 750 750 0
AVERAGE 600 650 50

To say that prep courses cause an increase in SAT scores, we mean that in an imaginary counterfactual world where the people who didn’t take the prep course had actually taken the course, then their SAT scores would be 50 points higher, on average.

This is the idea behind causation within the potential outcomes framework.

If we could observe everyone’s potential outcome (as in the above table), then finding evidence of causation is easy! We would even be able to identify the causal effect for each individual.

Of course, we cannot observe these counterfactual worlds. In the real world, people either attend the prep course, or they didn’t. In other words, our real-world data look something like this:

Illustration of potential outcomes, depending on whether an individual takes a prep course
SAT if no prep SAT if prep Difference
Alex ? 670 ?
Bonnie 500 ? ?
Colin 550 ? ?
Danielle ? 690 ?
Earl 600 ? ?
Fiona ? 720 ?
Gaston 400 ? ?
Hermine ? 750 ?

Since we do not observe counterfactual outcomes, we cannot estimate a separate treatment effect for each individual.

But with random assignment, we can estimate an average treatment effect (ATE) for the population.

Suppose we have a population N=1000.

We randomly assign 500 of them to take the prep course (and they actually attend all sessions). Let’s call these people the treatment group (T), and let’s call their SAT scores treatment outcomes.

The other 500 people who do not attend the prep course constitute the control group (C). Their SAT scores constitute the control outcomes.

Class Questions:

  1. Suppose that the average of the observed treatment outcomes = 650. What is your estimate of the average of all of the potential treatment outcomes?
  2. Similarly, suppose that the average of the observed control outcomes = 600. What is your estimate of the average of all of the potential control outcomes?
Key Takeaway


Since you have randomly assigned people to T and C, you can think of the observed outcomes as a random sample of all potential outcomes.

By implication, the average observed outcomes constitute an unbiased estimate of the average potential outcomes.

Thus the average difference in observed outcomes constitutes an unbiased causal estimate of the ATE.

Selection Bias without Random Assignment

Consider this table again, in comparison to the full schedule of potential outcomes
Potential C Potential T Observed C Observed T
Alex 650 670 ? 670
Bonnie 500 580 500 ?
Colin 550 550 550 ?
Danielle 700 690 ? 690
Earl 600 660 600 ?
Fiona 650 720 ? 720
Gaston 400 580 400 ?
Hermine 750 750 ? 750
AVERAGE 600 650 512.5 707.5

Class Questions:

  1. Here, the difference in average treatment and control outcomes is 195, which is much larger than the ATE of 50. Looking at the full schedule of potential outcomes, can you figure out why?
  2. Suppose that we obtain these results from an observational study, where subjects themselves choose whether they want to take part in the prep class. Why is this problematic?
  3. Suppose instead that our randomization procedure just happened to assign Alex, Danielle, Fiona and Hermine to treatment. Is our estimate of the ATE biased?
Key Takeaway


If we allow people to self-select in T and C, we can no longer consider the observed treatment/control outcomes as a random sample of all potential treatment/control outcomes. Thus, our basis for assessing causality falls apart.

In the absence of random assignment, estimates of the ATE may be biased (here: ability is a confounding variable).

Randomization solves this problem by making sure that potential outcomes are, on average, statistically independent of the treatments that subjects receive.

Thus, on average, ability (plus all other possible confounding variables) is equalized between T and C.

Another example: a researcher wants to know how winning large sums of money in a national lottery affects peoples views about inheritance taxes. The researcher interviews a random sample of adults and compares the attitudes of those who report winning more than $10,000 in the lottery to those who claim to have won little or nothing. The researcher reasons that the lottery chooses winners at random, and therefore the amount that people report having won is random.

Class Questions:

  1. Is this sound reasoning? In other words, are the potential outcomes of those who report winning more than $10,000 identical, in expectation, to those who report winning little or nothing?
  2. Suppose the researcher were to restrict the sample to people who had played the lottery at least once during the past year. Is it now safe to assume that the potential outcomes of those who report winning more than $10,000 are identical, in expectation, to those who report winning little or nothing?

Assumptions

Excludability

Potential outcomes respond solely to receipt of the treatment, not to the assignment itself or any indirect by-products of the assignment.

Here’s an example. Suppose you want to test the effectiveness of a new medication. You recruit a sample of people who are interested in the medication, and randomly divide them into treatment and control groups.

The treatment group is asked to take the medication in the form of a pill. The control group is told that their purpose is to serve as comparison group, and thus will not be receiving the medication.

Two research assistants – Karl and Lenny – are in charge of conducting the study. Lenny measures outcomes for the control group, while Karl measures outcomes from the treatment group.

Class Question:

  1. How might this design violate the excludability assumption?

Here’s another example. Suppose researchers seek to assess the effect of receiving a free newspaper subscription on students’ interest in politics. A list of student dorm rooms is drawn up and sorted randomly. Dorm rooms in the first half of the randomly sorted list receive a newspaper at their door each morning for two months; dorm rooms in the second half of the list do not receive a paper.

University researchers are sometimes required to disclose to subjects that they are participating in an experiment. Suppose that prior to the experiment, researchers distributed a letter informing students in the treatment group that they would be receiving a newspaper as part of a study to see if newspapers make students more interested in politics.

Class Question:

  1. How might this disclosure jeopardize the excludability assumption?

Non-interference (SUTVA)

Potential outcomes for each individual reflect only the treatment or control status of that individual and not the treatment or control status of other individuals. No matter which subjects the random assignment allocates to treatment or control, a given subject’s potential outcomes remain the same.

This idea is commonly termed the stable unit treatment value assumption (SUTVA).

Here is a schedule of potential outcomes containing a SUTVA violation
Aly C, Bob C Aly C, Bob T Aly T, Bob C Aly T, Bob T
Aly 650 650 670 670
Bob 500 520 580 600

A researcher studying 1,000 prison inmates noticed that prisoners who spend at least three hours per day reading are less likely to have violent encounters with other prisoners. The researcher therefore recommends that all prisoners be required to spend at least three hours reading each day.

Suppose that researchers were to test this researchers hypothesis by randomly assigning 10 prisoners to a treatment group. Prisoners in this group are required to go to the prison library and read in specially designated carrels for three hours each day for one week; the other prisoners, who make up the control group, go about their usual routines.

Class Questions:

  1. Can you state the non-interference assumption as it applies to this experiment? Do you think this assumption is met?
  2. Now let’s modify the design a bit. Suppose that every day, researchers toss a coin. If heads, then all prisoners go about their usual routines. If tails, then all prisoners are assigned to read for 3 hours in the library. The researchers the compare the average number of violent encounters on “normal days” vs “library days”. Does this solve the SUTVA problem?
